    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the context of tax reform, there is no consensus, as empirical results can vary widely. While some models and case studies suggest that tax cuts can lead to increased investment and job creation, critics emphasize that this may not necessarily translate to widespread wealth distribution. The stimulus argument, often championed by the supply-side economics school of thought – or as it's colloquially known, Milton Friedmanites – contends that lower taxes promote economic growth by increasing consumer spending and investment. However, the data can be mixed, with some research indicating modest benefits while others suggest negligible or even negative impacts on income inequality. In the case of the proposed 2024 tax reform, economists will need to analyze incoming data to see if it supports the stimulus argument or aligns more closely with critics' projections of increasing wealth inequality.",
